     =\n}}\n\nThe '''Municipality of Metlika''' ({{IPA-sl|m\u025b\u02c8tli\u02d0ka|pron|Sl-Metlika.ogg}}; {{lang-sl|Ob\u010dina Metlika}}) is a [[municipality]] in the traditional region of [[Lower Carniola]] in southeastern [[Slovenia]]. The seat of the municipality is the town of [[Metlika]]. Metlika became a municipality in 1994.<ref>{{cite book |title=Vzpostavitev lokalne samouprave v Republiki Sloveniji v \u0161tevilkah |date=2007 |publisher=Statisti\u010dni urad Republike Slovenije |location=Ljubljana |page=80|url=https://www.stat.si/StatWeb/File/DocSysFile/1290 |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Settlements==\nIn addition to the municipal seat of Metlika, the municipality also includes the following settlements:\n{{Div col|colwidth=14em}}\n* [[Bere\u010da Vas]]\n* [[Boginja Vas]]\n* [[Bojanja Vas]]\n* [[Boldra\u017e]]\n* [[Bor\u0161t, Metlika|Bor\u0161t]]\n* [[Bo\u017eakovo]]\n* [[Bo\u017ei\u010d Vrh]]\n* [[Brezovica pri Metliki]]\n* [[Bu\u0161inja Vas]]\n* [[\u010curile]]\n* [[Dole, Metlika|Dole]]\n* [[Dolnja Lokvica]]\n* [[Dolnje Dobravice]]\n* [[Dolnji Suhor pri Metliki]]\n* [[Drage, Metlika|Drage]]\n* [[Dragomlja Vas]]\n* [[Dra\u0161i\u010di]]\n* [[Ger\u0161i\u010di]]\n* [[Gornja Lokvica]]\n* [[Gornje Dobravice]]\n* [[Gornji Suhor pri Metliki]]\n* [[Grabrovec, Metlika|Grabrovec]]\n* [[Gradac, Metlika|Gradac]]\n* [[Grm pri Podzemlju]]\n* [[Hrast pri Jugorju]]\n* [[Jugorje pri Metliki]]\n* [[Kamenica, Metlika|Kamenica]]\n* [[Kaplji\u0161\u010de]]\n* [[Klo\u0161ter]]\n* [[Krasinec]]\n* [[Kra\u0161nji Vrh]]\n* [[Krivoglavice]]\n* [[Kri\u017eevska Vas, Metlika|Kri\u017eevska Vas]]\n* [[Krma\u010dina]]\n* [[Ma\u010dkovec pri Suhorju]]\n* [[Malo Le\u0161\u010de]]\n* [[Mlake, Metlika|Mlake]]\n* [[Okljuka]]\n* [[Otok, Metlika|Otok]]\n* [[Podzemelj]]\n* [[Prilozje]]\n* [[Primostek]]\n* [[Rado\u0161i, Metlika|Rado\u0161i]]\n* [[Radovica]]\n* [[Radovi\u010di]]\n* [[Rakovec, Metlika|Rakovec]]\n* [[Ravnace]]\n* [[Rosalnice]]\n* [[Sela pri Jugorju]]\n* [[\u0160kemljevec]]\n* [[\u0160krilje, Metlika|\u0160krilje]]\n* [[Slamna Vas]]\n* [[Svr\u017eaki]]\n* [[Trnovec, Metlika|Trnovec]]\n* [[Vido\u0161i\u010di]]\n* [[\u017delebej]]\n* [[\u017delezniki, Metlika|\u017delezniki]]\n* [[Zemelj]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline}}\n*[http://www.geopedia.si/#T105_F408:73_x524235.79650000005_y56135.2555_s12_b4 Municipality of Metlika on Geopedia]\n*[https://www.metlika.si/ Metlika municipal site]\n\n{{Geographic location\n | Centre = Metlika\n | N  = [[City Municipality of Novo Mesto|Novo Mesto]]\n | NE = {{flagicon|Croatia}} [[Ozalj]]\n | E  = {{flagicon|Croatia}} [[Kamanje]]<br/>{{flagicon|Croatia}} [[\u017dakanje]]\n | S  = [[Municipality of \u010crnomelj|\u010crnomelj]]\n | W  = [[Municipality of Semi\u010d|Semi\u010d]]\n}}\n{{Metlika}}\n{{Municipalities of Slovenia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Municipality of Metlika}}\n[[Category:Municipalities in Lower Carniola|Metlika]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Slovenia|Metlika]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in Slovenia]]\n", "name_user": "Ymblanter", "label": "safe", "comment": "+ short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Municipality_of_Metlika"}
{"title_page": "The Longest Journey", "text_new": "{{about|the computer game|the book by [[E. M. Forster]]|The Longest Journey (novel)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = The Longest Journey\n| image = longest.jpg\n| developer = [[Funcom]]\n| publisher = [[Empire Interactive]]<br>[[Tri Synergy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameindustry.com/reviews/game-review/the-longest-journey-is-paradise-found/ |title=The Longest Journey is Paradise Found - Gameindustry.com |date=February 21, 2001 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203121421/http://www.gameindustry.com/reviews/game-review/the-longest-journey-is-paradise-found/ |archivedate=February 3, 2015 }}</ref>\n| producer = [[Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist]]\n| designer = Didrik Tollefsen<br>Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist\n| programmer = Morten Lode<br>Audun T\u00f8rnquist\n| artist = Didrik Tollefsen\n| writer = Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist\n| composer = Bj\u00f8rn Arve Lagim\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[iOS]]\n| released = '''Windows'''{{Video game release|NOR|November 18, 1999<ref name=digino1 />|UK|April 20, 2000|NA|November 16, 2000}}'''iOS'''{{Video game release|AUS|October 28, 2014|WW|November 27, 2014}}\n| genre = [[Adventure game|Point-and-click adventure]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Longest Journey''''' is a [[Adventure game|point-and-click adventure video game]] developed by [[Norway|Norwegian]] studio [[Funcom]] for [[Microsoft Windows]] and released in 1999.\n\nThe game was a commercial success, with sales in excess of 500,000 units by 2004, and was acclaimed by critics. An [[iOS]] version was released on October 28, 2014.<ref name=\"ios\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-10-28-the-longest-journey-remastered-is-coming-to-ios-very-soon |title=The Longest Journey remastered is coming to iOS \"very soon\" |last=Matulef |first=Jeffrey |date=28 October 2014 |work=[[Eurogamer]] |publisher=Gamer Network |accessdate=27 November 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141202113857/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-10-28-the-longest-journey-remastered-is-coming-to-ios-very-soon |archivedate=December 2, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n''The Longest Journey'' is a [[point-and-click adventure game]] where the player interacts with objects on the screen to solve puzzles and advance the story. The game features expansive recorded dialogue, most of which is non-essential to completing the game but contributes to the setting.{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n==Plot <span id=\"plot\"></span>==\n{{long plot|date=July 2011}}\n\nThe game takes place in the parallel universes of [[magic (gaming)|magic-dominated]] Arcadia and industrial Stark. The protagonist, [[April Ryan (The Longest Journey)|April Ryan]], is an 18-year-old art student living in Stark, identified as a 'Shifter' capable of movement between these worlds, and tasked with restoring their essential Balance.\n\n[[File:Longest Journey screenshot.png|thumb|left|The player character, April Ryan, is standing in front of The Tree in her dream.]]\nThe story begins in Stark, where a sleeping April unintentionally shifts to Arcadia and meets the 'White Dragon', who identifies her as the heroine of the coming story. Upon learning this, April is attacked by a dark 'Chaos Vortex' and awakens in Stark, where she dismisses her experience as a nightmare. The character 'Cortez' later surprises her by revealing his knowledge.\n\nWhen surreal activity begins affecting her friends, April meets again with Cortez, who transports her to the Arcadian city Marcuria. There she meets Tobias Grensret, Vestrum of the Sentinel; learns Alltongue, the common language in Arcadia; and hears from Tobias that the Balance protecting both worlds is dissolving after the dereliction of its Guardian, and must be restored by the appearance of another.\n\nTo return to Stark, April visits Brian Westhouse, a friend of Cortez, who assists her return; Cortez then tells her of the organization known as the Vanguard or Church of Voltec. The next day, April consults Warren Hughes, a homeless boy who agrees to help April if she erases his criminal record and locates his missing sister, in doing which April finds a data cube on the Church of Voltec. Hughes then refers her to a hacker named Burns Flipper, who reveals that the wealthy magnate Jacob McAllen is head of the Vanguard, assisted by Gordon Halloway, a former candidate for Guardianship divided by the Vanguard into Chaos (in Arcadia) and Logic (in Stark), and gives her a false identification by which to infiltrate the Vanguard through its front company MTI.\n\nMeeting Cortez and Father Raul in a Catholic cathedral, April is told that Arcadia is on the brink of war. Later in Arcadia, April meets the innkeeper, Benrime Salmin, and the clairvoyant Abnaxus, ambassador of the Venar, who identifies the coming danger. In the morning, April learns of four magical species, each of whom has prophecies of a savior who will restore the Balance, only to finally break it \u2013 and determines to visit one such species, the winged Alatian of the island Alais, having gained sea-travel by rescuing a talking bird that she names Crow. Before departing, she learns that she must defeat an alchemist named Roper Klacks, in order to free the ships' wind that he holds captive.\n\nAt Roper Klacks' Tower, April challenges Klacks to use his magic against her calculator, and wins. Immediately before her departure to Alais, Tobias gives April the Talisman representing the Balance. ''En route'', April kills the monster known as 'Gribbler' while rescuing one of her captive Banda, whose species later give her the name 'April Bandu-embata' as a mark of gratitude and grant her part of the disc necessary to restore the Balance.\n\nOn the voyage to Alais, a 'Chaos Storm' attacks the ship, and April sabotages the ship's compass to restore its course. When the ship's captain seizes her Talisman, April attempts to retrieve it, and in so doing sinks the ship, whereupon the crew abandon her on a [[raft]]. She is taken prisoner by the Maerum, a [[Mermaid]]-like species related to the Alatian, but currently their enemies. In revealing their common ancestry, April fulfills a [[prophecy]] of the 'Waterstiller', a foretold savior of the Maerum.\n\nAfter fulfilling the second prophecy by killing a 'Snapjaw', she is conveyed to fulfill the third by re-uniting the Maerum with the Alatians. After a series of tasks and in meeting with the Alatians' leader, April fulfills their prophecy by flying without wings, and convinces the Alatian to make peace with the Maerum.\n\nIn a coastal sea cave, the Teller's guard and the Maerum Queen bring stones which combine to form the second part of the Balance's disc; whereupon the Maerum convey April, at her own request, to the Blue Dragon, who gives April one of the disc's Jewels and takes her to a ship inhabited by the Dark People, who give April the third piece of the disc, and an astral map locating the Guardian's Realm.\n\nAt the Marcurian Harbor, April is attacked by the Chaos and returns to the Cathedral in Stark. There, Father Raul reveals that he is also a Sentinel Minstrum of Stark, and that Cortez is missing. On returning to her lodgings, April is caught by Gordon Halloway. She is rescued by another character, Lady Alvane, who teaches April to shift at will, and sends April to Abnaxus to receive the disc's final piece. April then returns to the White Dragon, who reveals herself as April's mother and dies, and a new White Dragon emerges from her egg.\n\nReturned to Stark, April gives Flipper the star map to decipher, infiltrates MTI, and is captured by antagonist McAllen. Unable to escape, she surrenders her two jewels and the disc, and is then imprisoned. Upon escaping in pursuit of her object, she is trapped again; but rescued by Cortez. McAllen then reveals that he and Cortez are two Dragons (called 'Draic Kin', in-universe) meant to protect Stark, but at odds after McAllen's decision to re-unite the two worlds despite the risk of Chaos. The two then appear to die in combat. Retrieving the disc and the four jewels, April returns to Flipper, whom she finds dying after the seizure of her deciphered map by Gordon Halloway, and gains a copy from him, which she uses to locate the Guardian's Realm near the [[space station]] 'Morning Star'.\n\nAt the station, April frees Adrian, the derelict Guardian, and escapes with Halloway in pursuit. On her way to the Guardians' Tower, she imprisons the Chaos Vortex in her Talisman and later summons Crow, who helps her complete the necessary trials. Inside the tower, April re-unites Halloway with the Chaos Vortex to restore his candidacy as Guardian and returns to Stark and Arcadia.\n\nIn the Epilogue, the scene returns to Lady Alvane's home, where she has narrated the entire story to two youths, and where she reveals that the two worlds re-united under Gordon Halloway. Upon their departure, an aged and graying Crow enters, asking the tale of the \"[[Women warriors in literature and culture|warrior princess]]\" who won the war of the Balance, and she corrects his impression; a possible reference to the sequel, ''[[Dreamfall: The Longest Journey]]''.\n\n==Development==\nThe title of the game is a reference to the quote by the Swedish diplomat [[Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld]]: \"The longest journey is the journey inward, for he who has chosen his destiny has started upon his quest for the source of his being.\"<ref>{{cite AV media|people=Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist |date=22 February 2013 |title=RedThreadGames: Dreamfall Chapters: The Longest Journey |medium=live stream |url=http://www.twitch.tv/redthreadgames/b/370112870 |accessdate=27 February 2013 |time=10:01:20 |timecaption=Creator commentary starting at |publisher=[[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] |location=Oslo, Norway |display-authors=etal |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130226144439/http://www.twitch.tv/redthreadgames/b/370112870 |archivedate=February 26, 2013 }}</ref> Other inspirations for the game included ''[[Gabriel Knight: Sins of the Fathers]]'', [[Neil Gaiman]]'s ''[[The Sandman (Vertigo)|The Sandman]]'' and ''[[The Books of Magic]]'', ''[[Hellblazer]]'', ''[[Swamp Thing]]'', ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'', and [[Joss Whedon]]'s writing in general.<ref name=\"B\u00f6ke\"/>\n\n''The Longest Journey'' was developed by a small internal team at [[Funcom]] led by [[Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist]]. It was their first original project. Funcom put few restrictions on the developers except the budget (approx. $2\u20133 million) and the deadline. Since the team had to develop the [[game engine]] and most of the required tools from scratch, they struggled to release the game on time. For most of 1999, the team had to work overtime and during weekends to ultimately meet the deadline.<ref name=\"B\u00f6ke\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adventuregamers.com/articles/view/24090 |title=Dreamfall Chapters \u2013 Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist |last=B\u00f6ke |first=Ingmar |date=1 March 2013 |work=[[Adventure Gamers]] |accessdate=1 March 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304061953/http://www.adventuregamers.com/articles/view/24090 |archivedate=March 4, 2013 }}</ref> In the original Norwegian release, April Ryan was voiced by the journalist [[:no:Synn\u00f8ve Svab\u00f8|Synn\u00f8ve Svab\u00f8]].<ref name=dagbladet2>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000308132657/http://www.dagbladet.no:80/kultur/1999/06/30/169622.html | url=http://www.dagbladet.no:80/kultur/1999/06/30/169622.html | title=Synn\u00f8ve blir dataheltinne | date=June 30, 1999 | author=Andersen, Unn Conradi | work=[[Dagbladet]] | language=Norwegian | archivedate=March 8, 2000 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFirst published by IQ Media Nordic in Norway in 1999, it was later localized for and released in France, the United Kingdom, Germany, Italy, Belgium, the Netherlands, Canada, Spain, Denmark, Finland, Sweden, Poland, Czech Republic, Russia, and the United States. The game was originally written and recorded in English, though most of the localizations were released before the English version.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sluganski |first=Randy |title=Interview with Ragnar Tornquist |publisher=Just Adventure + |url=http://www.justadventure.com/Interviews/Ragnar_Tornquist/Ragnar_Tornquist.shtm |accessdate=2011-01-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610135459/http://www.justadventure.com/Interviews/Ragnar_Tornquist/Ragnar_Tornquist.shtm |archivedate=June 10, 2011 }}</ref> In October 2011, it was announced that ''The Longest Journey'' was being ported to [[iOS]], with the article mainly focusing on the [[iPhone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videogamer.com/pc/dreamfall/news/the_longest_journey_coming_to_iphone.html |title=The Longest Journey coming to iPhone - VideoGamer.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710155308/http://www.videogamer.com/pc/dreamfall/news/the_longest_journey_coming_to_iphone.html |archivedate=July 10, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Release and sales==\nBefore its release, ''The Longest Journey'' received positive preview coverage and was heavily promoted in Norway.<ref name=digino1>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050217222220/http://digi.no/php/art.php?id=43949 | url=http://digi.no/php/art.php?id=43949 | title=\"Den lengste reisen\" i m\u00e5l etter halvannen m\u00e5ned | author=Berg, Herman | date=December 29, 1999 | work=[[Digi.no]] | language=Norwegian | archivedate=February 17, 2005 | url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[Dagbladet]]'' described the title as \"the first big Norwegian computer game.\" Its target demographics were outside the industry's norm: Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist reported that Funcom wanted to capture \"a more adult audience in addition to the usual teenage buyers\". The game's high budget meant that 150,000 sales were necessary to [[Break-even|break even]].<ref name=dagbladet1 /> However, Norway's market for games was small.<ref name=digino1 /><ref name=dagbladet1 /> According to Herman Berg of [[Digi.no]], it was rare for a game's Norwegian sales to reach 10,000 units.<ref name=digino1 /> ''The Longest Journey''{{'}}s domestic sales goal was 15,000 units,<ref name=digino1 /><ref name=dagbladet1>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010417122346/http://www.dagbladet.no/kultur/1999/11/19/183637.html | url=http://www.dagbladet.no/kultur/1999/11/19/183637.html | title=Norske April blir data-babe | author=Hanssen, Kurt | date=November 19, 1999 | work=[[Dagbladet]] | language=Norwegian | archivedate=April 17, 2001 | url-status=dead }}</ref> while its global lifetime goal was 300,000 units.<ref name=vg1>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001008063343/http://www.vg.no/pub/vgart.hbs?artid=3762419 | url=http://www.vg.no/pub/vgart.hbs?artid=3762419 | title=Redder verden i norsk dataspill | date=November 19, 1999 | author=Winterkj\u00e6r, St\u00e5le | work=[[Verdens Gang]] | language=Norwegian | archivedate=October 8, 2000 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Funcom shipped 15,000 copies of ''The Longest Journey'' to Norwegian retailers in the game's first month and a half on shelves, and publisher IQ Media noted that [[sell-through]] and store re-orders were high through late December. Sell-in had reached 10,000 units in Sweden by that time. Based on the available data, IQ's Nickolay Nickelsen noted that it \"looks as if half of the players are actually girls.\"<ref name=digino1 />\n\nAccording to T\u00f8rnquist, ''The Longest Journey'' experienced \"solid sales across Europe\" before its release in the United States.<ref name=ragnarint>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050405105813/http://www.justadventure.com/Interviews/Ragnar_Tornquist/Ragnar_Tornquist.shtm | url=http://www.justadventure.com:80/Interviews/Ragnar_Tornquist/Ragnar_Tornquist.shtm | title=Ragnar Tornquist | author=Sluganski, Randy | archivedate=April 5, 2005 | work=[[Just Adventure]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The game sold 15,000 units in Norway by May 2000,<ref name=bonusweb>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000916223844/http://www.bonusweb.cz:80/interview/ragnartornquist.html | url=http://www.bonusweb.cz:80/interview/ragnartornquist.html | title=Ragnar Tornquist o ''The Longest Journey'' | date=May 22, 2000 | author=Tichacek, Petr | work=BonusWeb | archivedate=September 16, 2000 | url-status=dead }}</ref> while overall European sales totaled 100,000 units by September 2000.<ref name=digino2>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050219225758/http://digi.no/digi98.nsf/pub/dd20000928104026pc28450446| url=http://digi.no/digi98.nsf/pub/dd20000928104026pc28450446 | title=Eventyrdame med lang reise til USA | author=Sokke, Christian | date=September 28, 2000 | work=[[Digi.no]] | language=Norwegian | archivedate=February 19, 2005 | url-status=dead }}</ref> It launched in Germany with a shipment of 40,000 units to retailers;<ref name=digino3>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050313185329/http://www.digi.no/digi98.nsf/pub/md20000317010000pcs2703135729| url=http://www.digi.no/digi98.nsf/pub/md20000317010000pcs2703135729 | title=April Ryans lange reise til England | author=Sokke, Christian | date=March 17, 2000 | work=[[Digi.no]] | archivedate=March 13, 2005 | url-status=dead | language=Norwegian }}</ref><ref name=40k>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011211090046/http://www.longestjourney.com:80/news.html | url=http://www.longestjourney.com:80/news.html | title=German release date March 20th | date=February 15, 2000 | archivedate=December 11, 2001 | publisher=[[Funcom]] | url-status=dead }}</ref> Chris Kellner of [[DTP Entertainment]], which handled the game's German localization, reported its lifetime sales between 10,000 and 50,000 copies in that market.<ref name=inv10>{{cite magazine | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060813153740/http://www.justadventure.com:80/TheInventory/TheInventory.shtm | url=http://www.justadventure.com:80/TheInventory/TheInventory.shtm | title=The Lounge; Interview with DTP | date=November 2003 | issue=10 | magazine=The Inventory | publisher=[[Just Adventure]] | archivedate=August 13, 2006 | pages=20\u201323 | url-status=dead }}</ref> In Spain, the game sold 50,000 copies after roughly one year, a commercial hit for the country.<ref name=50k>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040907063053/http://www.meristation.com:80/sc/noticias/noticia.asp?c=GEN&n=3527| url=http://www.meristation.com:80/sc/noticias/noticia.asp?c=GEN&n=3527 | title=''The Longest Journey'' proporciona a FX su cuarto CD-ROM de oro | date=November 14, 2001 | author=Meix, Joan Isern | work=MeriStation | archivedate=September 7, 2004 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Its English release was purposely delayed to prevent imports from [[Cannibalization (marketing)|cannibalizing]] local sales across Europe.<ref name=nettavisen1>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000301145118/http://www.nettavisen.no/it_nyheter/82013.html | url=http://www.nettavisen.no/it_nyheter/82013.html | title=Lettere animert Synn\u00f8ve Svab\u00f8 | author=Heft\u00f8y, Jens Egil | date=November 19, 1999 | work=[[Nettavisen]] | language=Norwegian | archivedate=March 1, 2000 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n''The Longest Journey'' struggled to find a North American publisher.<ref name=granade>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010428224705/http://interactfiction.about.com/games/interactfiction/library/weekly/aa101600a.htm |url=http://interactfiction.about.com/games/interactfiction/library/weekly/aa101600a.htm | title=Journey to America | author=Granade, Stephen | work=[[About.com]] | date=October 16, 2000 | archivedate=April 28, 2001 | url-status=dead }}</ref> According to market research firm [[PC Data]], North American sales of ''The Longest Journey'' reached 12,495 retail units by the end of 2000, of which 10,873 were sold in December.<ref name=randysales>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010414041809/http://justadventure.com/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/01-02/Feb_01.asp | url=http://justadventure.com:80/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/01-02/Feb_01.asp | title=The State of Adventure Gaming | date=February 2001 | author=Sluganski, Randy | archivedate=April 14, 2001 | work=[[Just Adventure]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> By January 2001, global sales of ''The Longest Journey'' totaled almost 200,000 units.<ref name=200k>{{cite press release | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011106042732/http://www.funcom.com:80/corporate/about/pressreleases/100101tljawards.html | url=http://www.funcom.com:80/corporate/about/pressreleases/100101tljawards.html | title=Norsk dataspill til topps i USA | date=January 10, 2001 | location=[[Oslo]] | publisher=[[Funcom]] | archivedate=November 6, 2001 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=digino4>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050217084422/http://www.digi.no/digi98.nsf/pub/dd20010110104314tw36623025 | url=http://www.digi.no/digi98.nsf/pub/dd20010110104314tw36623025 | title=Norsk spill-suksess i USA | author=Werenskiold, Therese | date=January 10, 2001 | work=[[Digi.no]] | language=Norwegian | archivedate=February 17, 2005 | url-status=dead }}</ref> PC Data reported an additional 40,160 retail sales of ''The Longest Journey'' in North America during the first six months of 2001.<ref name=randysales2>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020215014752/http://justadventure.com/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/01-08/August_01.shtm | url=http://justadventure.com:80/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/01-08/August_01.shtm | title=The State of Adventure Gaming | author=Sluganski, Randy | date=August 2001 | archivedate=February 15, 2002 | work=[[Just Adventure]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> By that June, the game's worldwide sales had climbed to 250,000 copies, of which the United States accounted for 90,000.<ref name=gamespotsales>{{cite web |last=Park |first=Andrew |title=''The Longest Journey'' sells 250,000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011126033629/http://gamespot.com/gamespot/stories/news/0,10870,2779455,00.html |url=http://gamespot.com:80/gamespot/stories/news/0,10870,2779455,00.html |archivedate=November 26, 2001 |date=June 22, 2001 |work=[[GameSpot]] |url-status=dead }}</ref> PC Data's estimate for the title's North American sales for January\u2013December 2001 was 71,962 retail units,<ref name=randysales3>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020619111456/http://www.justadventure.com/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/Mar-02/sales2001.shtm | url=http://www.justadventure.com:80/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/Mar-02/sales2001.shtm | title=State of Adventure Gaming - March 2002 - 2001 Sales Table | date=March 2002 | author=Sluganski, Randy | archivedate=June 19, 2002 | work=[[Just Adventure]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> followed by another 12,044 in the first six months of 2002.<ref name=randysales4>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050314010007/http://justadventure.com/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/August2002/SalesJune2002.shtm | url=http://justadventure.com:80/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/August2002/SalesJune2002.shtm | title=State of Adventure Gaming - August 2002 - June 2002 Sales Table | date=August 2002 | author=Sluganski, Randy | archivedate=March 14, 2005 | work=[[Just Adventure]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> By July 2002, global sales of the game had reached 450,000 copies, according to Funcom. A new shipment was released in North America that month, as its earlier printing had sold out.<ref name=450k>{{cite web | title = ''The Longest Journey'' \u2013 General News | publisher = [[Funcom]] | author=Staff | url = http://www.longestjourney.com/news/general/ | date = July 29, 2002 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20021010033406/http://www.longestjourney.com/news/general/ |archivedate = October 10, 2002}}</ref> Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist noted in 2003 that he was \"very satisfied\" with ''The Longest Journey''{{'}}s sales in North America, and explained, \"There was such strong word of mouth, and so many great reviews, that we managed to get ''TLJ'' into most big stores and out to the players regardless of marketing.\"<ref name=ragnarint2>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050308133426/http://www.justadventure.com/Interviews/TLJ2/TLJ2.shtm | url=http://www.justadventure.com:80/Interviews/TLJ2/TLJ2.shtm | title=An Interview with Ragnar Tornquist | date=February 27, 2003 | author=Sluganski, Randy | archivedate=March 8, 2005 | work=[[Just Adventure]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2003, Marek Bronstring of [[Adventure Gamers]] wrote that ''The Longest Journey'' \"sold half a million copies worldwide and it's still selling, making it one of the most successful adventure games in recent years.\"<ref name=tlj2prev>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020085804/http://www.adventuregamers.com/display.php?id=262 | url=http://www.adventuregamers.com/display.php?id=262 | title=''The Longest Journey 2'' Archived Preview | author=Bronstring, Marek | date=May 24, 2003 | work=[[Adventure Gamers]] | archivedate=October 20, 2007 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The following year, [[IGN]] reported that its sales had surpassed 500,000 units. The site's Richard Aihoshi summarized ''The Longest Journey'' as a \"a critical and commercial success\".<ref name=ignint2>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040602200352/http://rpgvault.ign.com/articles/512/512726p1.html | url=http://rpgvault.ign.com:80/articles/512/512726p1.html | title=''Dreamfall - The Longest Journey'' Interview | date=May 10, 2004 | author=Aihoshi, Richard | work=[[IGN]] | archivedate=June 2, 2004 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2019, T\u00f8rnquist recalled that \"at least 50 per cent\" of ''The Longest Journey''{{'}}s players were female, a fact that he believed increased its commercial success.<ref name=retrogamer>{{cite journal | author=Walker-Emig, Paul | title=The Making of ''The Longest Journey'' | date=2019 | issue=191 | work=[[Retro Gamer]] | pages=66\u201369 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| GR = 88.00%<ref name=\"GR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/198973-the-longest-journey/index.html |title=The Longest Journey for PC |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=30 March 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316210557/http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/198973-the-longest-journey/index.html |archivedate=March 16, 2009 }}</ref>\n| MC = 91/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-longest-journey |title=The Longest Journey for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=30 March 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100820025358/http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-longest-journey |archivedate=August 20, 2010 }}</ref>\n| CGW = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=cgw>{{cite journal | author=Wells, Audrey | title=Fantastic Voyage | date=January 2001 | issue=198 | journal=[[Computer Gaming World]] | pages=138, 139 }}</ref>\n| AdvGamers = 4.5/5<ref name=\"advgamers_review\">{{cite web|last=Bronstring |first=Marek |date=20 May 2000 |url=http://www.adventuregamers.com/articles/view/17507 |title=The Longest Journey |publisher=[[Adventure Gamers]] |accessdate=30 March 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615113941/http://www.adventuregamers.com/articles/view/17507 |archivedate=June 15, 2012 }}</ref>\n| GSpot = 9.3/10<ref name=\"gamespot review\">{{cite web|last=Dulin |first=Ron |date=26 June 2000 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/pc/adventure/longestjourney/review.html?mode=gsreview |title=The Longest Journey for PC Review |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=29 March 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060619134056/http://www.gamespot.com/pc/adventure/longestjourney/review.html?mode=gsreview |archivedate=June 19, 2006 }}</ref>\n| GSpy = 92/100<ref name=\"gamespy_review\">{{cite web|last=Schembri |first=Tamara |url=http://archive.gamespy.com/legacy/reviews/tlj_a.shtm |title=The Longest Journey |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |accessdate=30 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409005858/http://archive.gamespy.com/legacy/reviews/tlj_a.shtm |archivedate=April 9, 2008 }}</ref>\n| IGN = 9.3/10<ref name=\"ign review\">{{cite web|last=Lopez |first=Vincent |date=20 November 2000 |url=http://pc.ign.com/articles/160/160848p1.html |title=The Longest Journey Review |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=29 March 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509100616/http://pc.ign.com/articles/160/160848p1.html |archivedate=May 9, 2008 }}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 90%<ref name=\"pcgamer us\">{{cite journal |last=Steinberg |first=Scott |date=February 2001 |title=The Longest Journey |journal=[[PC Gamer|PC Gamer US]] |volume=8 |issue=2 |pages=97 |issn=1080-4471 }}</ref>\n| NGen = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=nextgenrev>{{cite journal | author=Bratcher, Eric | title=Finals; ''The Longest Journey'' | date=February 2001 | page=83 | journal=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] | volume=Lifecycle 2, Vol. 3 | number=2 }}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Computer Games Magazine]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=cgm>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040813082453/http://www.cgonline.com/reviews/longestjou-01-r1.html | url=http://www.cgonline.com:80/reviews/longestjou-01-r1.html | title=Review; ''The Longest Journey'' | author=Morgan, Cindy Kyser | date=February 26, 2001 | archivedate=August 13, 2004 | work=[[Computer Games Magazine]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[EP Daily|The Electric Playground]]''\n| rev4Score = 8.5/10<ref name=elecplay>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040126204016/http://elecplay.com/review.html?article=5148 | url=http://www.elecplay.com:80/review.html?article=5148 | title=''The Longest Journey'' | author=Reaume, Paula | date=February 1, 2001 | archivedate=January 26, 2004 | work=[[EP Daily|The Electric Playground]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n\n''The Longest Journey'' was acclaimed by critics. It was praised for its female protagonist [[April Ryan (The Longest Journey)|April Ryan]], who is considered one of the most memorable female characters in the history of [[adventure game]]s,<ref name=\"GPro_TLJ_rev\">{{cite magazine |last=Molloy |first=Sean |date=23 February 2004 |url=http://www.gamepro.com/computer/pc/games/reviews/7526.shtml |title=''The Longest Journey'' review |magazine=[[GamePro]] |accessdate=14 December 2006 |quote=April Ryan is one of the strongest, most well-written, and most likeable heroines ever to point-and-click her way around a PC game. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517050706/http://www.gamepro.com/computer/pc/games/reviews/7526.shtml |archivedate=May 17, 2008 }}</ref> and also for its enigmatic, complex storyline and high production values, but was criticized for some of its more obscure puzzles. It received a score of 88.00% on [[GameRankings]]<ref name=\"GR\" /> and 91/100 on [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MC\" /> [[GameSpot]] called it \"one of the best adventure games in years\" and applauded the \"complex and interesting story\" although found the ending lacking as \"the [[epilogue]] does little to wrap everything up\".<ref name=\"gamespot review\" /> ''[[IGN]]'' said the game \"actually reinvents how stories can be told in the medium\" and noticed the mature content, including \"harsh subject matter, and some big time swearing\". Some of the puzzles were described as \"inane\", but on the whole the game \"hones the genre into its tightest, sharpest form yet\".<ref name=\"ign review\" /> The US edition of ''[[PC Gamer]]'' praised the \"mature and magical\" story, the \"sumptuous\" graphics, and the game's puzzles.<ref name=\"pcgamer us\" /> The only criticism levied by the magazine was that some parts of the game might be \"too edgy\" for younger players.<ref name=\"pcgamer us\" />\n\nEric Bratcher reviewed the PC version of the game for ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'', rating it three stars out of five, and stated that \"This is a potential epic that seems to have taken tranquilizers. It's still worthwhile, but it's also a little slow, a little dull, and sometimes just doesn't make sense.\"<ref name=nextgenrev/>\n\n''The Longest Journey'' was named the best computer adventure game of 2000 by ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'',<ref name=cgwpremier2000>{{cite journal | author=Staff | journal=[[Computer Gaming World]] | title=The 2001 Premier Awards; Games of the Year |date=April 2001 | issue=201 | pages=72\u201380, 82, 83 }}</ref> ''[[EP Daily|The Electric Playground]]'',<ref name=blister2000>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020208192633/http://www.elecplay.com/feature.html?article=5130&page=1 | url=http://www.elecplay.com/feature.html?article=5130&page=1 | title=Blister Awards 2000 | date=February 2001 | author=Staff | work=[[EP Daily|The Electric Playground]] | archivedate=February 8, 2002 | url-status=dead }}</ref> [[GameSpot]],<ref name=gamespot2000>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020202174438/http://gamespot.com/gamespot/features/pc/bestof_2000/index.html |url=http://gamespot.com:80/gamespot/features/pc/bestof_2000/index.html |title=Best and Worst of 2000 |author=GameSpot Staff |work=[[GameSpot]] |archivedate=February 2, 2002 | date=January 5, 2001 | url-status=dead }}</ref> [[IGN]] and ''[[PC Gamer US]]'',<ref name=ignawards2000>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010413122552/http://pc.ign.com/news/30575.html |url=http://pc.ign.com:80/news/30575.html |title=IGNPC's Best of 2000 Awards |author=Staff |work=[[IGN]] |archivedate=April 13, 2001 |date=January 26, 2001 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=pcgseventh>{{cite magazine | title=The Seventh Annual PC Gamer Awards | magazine=PC Gamer | publisher=[[Imagine Media]] | issn=1080-4471 | volume=3 | issue=8 | date=March 2001 }}</ref> and was nominated in the category by [[CNET Gamecenter]] and ''[[Computer Games Magazine]]''.<ref name=cgmnominees>{{cite web |author=Staff |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050209070529/http://www.cdmag.com/articles/031/125/010208-07.html |url=http://www.cdmag.com:80/articles/031/125/010208-07.html |title=''Computer Games Magazine'' announces nominees for annual best in computer gaming awards |date=February 8, 2001 |work=[[Computer Games Magazine]] |archivedate=February 9, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=gamecenter2000>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010208100435/http://www.gamecenter.com/Features/Exclusives/Awards2k/ | url=http://www.gamecenter.com:80/Features/Exclusives/Awards2k/ | title=Gamecenter's computer game awards for 2000 | author=The Gamecenter Editors | work=[[CNET Gamecenter]] | date=January 25, 2001 | archivedate=February 8, 2001 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> It also won IGN's \"Best Game No One Played\" and GameSpot's \"Best Story\" awards.<ref name=ignawards2000 /><ref name=gamespot2000 /> ''Computer Gaming World''{{'}}s editors praised the game for offering \"a mature, literate, and compelling story featuring a strong female heroine who, for once, is not exploited for her looks.\"<ref name=cgwpremier2000 />\n\nIn 2011, [[Adventure Gamers]] named ''The Longest Journey'' the second-best adventure game ever released.<ref name=top100>{{cite web | author=AG Staff | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604021011/http://www.adventuregamers.com/articles/view/18643 | url=http://www.adventuregamers.com/articles/view/18643 | title=Top 100 All-Time Adventure Games | date=December 30, 2011 | archivedate=June 4, 2012 | work=[[Adventure Gamers]] | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Sequels==\nA sequel to ''The Longest Journey'' began production in early 2003.<ref name=dagbladet3>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050421224201/http://www.dagbladet.no:80/kultur/2003/03/01/362829.html| url=http://www.dagbladet.no:80/kultur/2003/03/01/362829.html | title=Den ''lengste'' lengste reisen | author=Bryne, Snorre | date=March 1, 2003 | work=[[Dagbladet]] | archivedate=April 21, 2005 | language=Norwegian | url-status=dead }}</ref> The game, ''[[Dreamfall: The Longest Journey]]'', was released in April 2006. The next installment of the series, ''[[Dreamfall Chapters]]'', was crowd-funded on [[Kickstarter]] and was released [[episodic video game|episodically]]. Its first episode was released in October 2014.<ref name=\"DFC_Kickstarter\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/redthread/dreamfall-chapters-the-longest-journey |title=Dreamfall Chapters: The Longest Journey |last=Red Thread Games |date=8 February 2013 |work=[[Kickstarter]] |accessdate=8 February 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130211002220/http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/redthread/dreamfall-chapters-the-longest-journey |archivedate=February 11, 2013 }}</ref> The last episode shipped in June 2016.\n\nThe developers view ''Dreamfall: The Longest Journey'' as more of a [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] than a direct [[sequel]] to the first game, as it revolves around a new protagonist, with a new storyline.<ref name=\"B\u00f6ke\" /> The direct sequel to ''The Longest Journey'', entitled ''The Longest Journey Home'', was revealed in 2013 and is to be produced after ''Dreamfall Chapters''.<ref name=\"TLJHome\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/features/taking-the-longest-journey-home-6404653/ |title=Taking The Longest Journey Home |last=VanOrd |first=Kevin |date=1 March 2013 |work=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=4 March 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304090413/http://www.gamespot.com/features/taking-the-longest-journey-home-6404653/ |archivedate=March 4, 2013 }}</ref> By 2016 the release of TLJHome is still under a question. Ragnar Tornquist stated that even though he wants to produce the game, there are many reasons why it may never happen.<ref name=\"Hillier2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2016/06/10/dreamfall-chapters-teaser-heralds-the-end-of-the-longest-journey/ |title=Dreamfall Chapters teaser heralds the end of The Longest Journey |last=Hillier |first=Brenna |date=10 June 2016 |work=[[VG247]] |accessdate=13 June 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611142231/http://www.vg247.com/2016/06/10/dreamfall-chapters-teaser-heralds-the-end-of-the-longest-journey/ |archivedate=June 11, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"O'Connor\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/06/10/when-does-dreamfall-chapters-book-five-come-out/ |title=Dreamfall Chapters Ending Longest Journey Next Week |last=O'Connor |first=Alice |date=10 June 2016 |work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] |accessdate=17 June 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611135824/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/06/10/when-does-dreamfall-chapters-book-five-come-out/ |archivedate=June 11, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Runaway: A Road Adventure]]''\n*''[[Syberia]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.longestjourney.com}}\n* {{moby game|id=/longest-journey}}\n\n{{The Longest Journey}}\n{{Funcom}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Longest Journey, The}}\n[[Category:1999 video games]]\n[[Category:Funcom games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Point-and-click adventure games]]\n[[Category:The Longest Journey games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Norway]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female protagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring parallel universes]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:ResidualVM supported games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the computer game|the book by [[E. M. Forster]]|The Longest Journey (novel)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = The Longest Journey\n| image = longest.jpg\n| developer = [[Funcom]]\n| publisher = [[Empire Interactive]]<br>[[Tri Synergy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameindustry.com/reviews/game-review/the-longest-journey-is-paradise-found/ |title=The Longest Journey is Paradise Found - Gameindustry.com |date=February 21, 2001 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203121421/http://www.gameindustry.com/reviews/game-review/the-longest-journey-is-paradise-found/ |archivedate=February 3, 2015 }}</ref>\n| producer = [[Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist]]\n| designer = Didrik Tollefsen<br>Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist\n| programmer = Morten Lode<br>Audun T\u00f8rnquist\n| artist = Didrik Tollefsen\n| writer = Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist\n| composer = Bj\u00f8rn Arve Lagim\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[iOS]]\n| released = '''Windows'''{{Video game release|NOR|November 18, 1999<ref name=digino1 />|UK|April 20, 2000|NA|November 16, 2000}}'''iOS'''{{Video game release|AUS|October 28, 2014|WW|November 27, 2014}}\n| genre = [[Adventure game|Point-and-click adventure]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Longest Journey''''' is a [[Adventure game|point-and-click adventure video game]] developed by [[Norway|Norwegian]] studio [[Funcom]] for [[Microsoft Windows]] and released in 1999.\n\nThe game was a commercial success, with sales in excess of 500,000 units by 2004, and was acclaimed by critics. An [[iOS]] version was released on October 28, 2014.<ref name=\"ios\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-10-28-the-longest-journey-remastered-is-coming-to-ios-very-soon |title=The Longest Journey remastered is coming to iOS \"very soon\" |last=Matulef |first=Jeffrey |date=28 October 2014 |work=[[Eurogamer]] |publisher=Gamer Network |accessdate=27 November 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141202113857/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-10-28-the-longest-journey-remastered-is-coming-to-ios-very-soon |archivedate=December 2, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n''The Longest Journey'' is a [[point-and-click adventure game]] where the player interacts with objects on the screen to solve puzzles and advance the story. The game features expansive recorded dialogue, most of which is non-essential to completing the game but contributes to the setting.{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n==Plot==\n{{long plot|date=July 2011}}\n\nThe game takes place in the parallel universes of [[magic (gaming)|magic-dominated]] Arcadia and industrial Stark. The protagonist, [[April Ryan (The Longest Journey)|April Ryan]], is an 18-year-old art student living in Stark, identified as a 'Shifter' capable of movement between these worlds, and tasked with restoring their essential Balance.\n\n[[File:Longest Journey screenshot.png|thumb|left|The player character, April Ryan, is standing in front of The Tree in her dream.]]\nThe story begins in Stark, where a sleeping April unintentionally shifts to Arcadia and meets the 'White Dragon', who identifies her as the heroine of the coming story. Upon learning this, April is attacked by a dark 'Chaos Vortex' and awakens in Stark, where she dismisses her experience as a nightmare. The character 'Cortez' later surprises her by revealing his knowledge.\n\nWhen surreal activity begins affecting her friends, April meets again with Cortez, who transports her to the Arcadian city Marcuria. There she meets Tobias Grensret, Vestrum of the Sentinel; learns Alltongue, the common language in Arcadia; and hears from Tobias that the Balance protecting both worlds is dissolving after the dereliction of its Guardian, and must be restored by the appearance of another.\n\nTo return to Stark, April visits Brian Westhouse, a friend of Cortez, who assists her return; Cortez then tells her of the organization known as the Vanguard or Church of Voltec. The next day, April consults Warren Hughes, a homeless boy who agrees to help April if she erases his criminal record and locates his missing sister, in doing which April finds a data cube on the Church of Voltec. Hughes then refers her to a hacker named Burns Flipper, who reveals that the wealthy magnate Jacob McAllen is head of the Vanguard, assisted by Gordon Halloway, a former candidate for Guardianship divided by the Vanguard into Chaos (in Arcadia) and Logic (in Stark), and gives her a false identification by which to infiltrate the Vanguard through its front company MTI.\n\nMeeting Cortez and Father Raul in a Catholic cathedral, April is told that Arcadia is on the brink of war. Later in Arcadia, April meets the innkeeper, Benrime Salmin, and the clairvoyant Abnaxus, ambassador of the Venar, who identifies the coming danger. In the morning, April learns of four magical species, each of whom has prophecies of a savior who will restore the Balance, only to finally break it \u2013 and determines to visit one such species, the winged Alatian of the island Alais, having gained sea-travel by rescuing a talking bird that she names Crow. Before departing, she learns that she must defeat an alchemist named Roper Klacks, in order to free the ships' wind that he holds captive.\n\nAt Roper Klacks' Tower, April challenges Klacks to use his magic against her calculator, and wins. Immediately before her departure to Alais, Tobias gives April the Talisman representing the Balance. ''En route'', April kills the monster known as 'Gribbler' while rescuing one of her captive Banda, whose species later give her the name 'April Bandu-embata' as a mark of gratitude and grant her part of the disc necessary to restore the Balance.\n\nOn the voyage to Alais, a 'Chaos Storm' attacks the ship, and April sabotages the ship's compass to restore its course. When the ship's captain seizes her Talisman, April attempts to retrieve it, and in so doing sinks the ship, whereupon the crew abandon her on a [[raft]]. She is taken prisoner by the Maerum, a [[Mermaid]]-like species related to the Alatian, but currently their enemies. In revealing their common ancestry, April fulfills a [[prophecy]] of the 'Waterstiller', a foretold savior of the Maerum.\n\nAfter fulfilling the second prophecy by killing a 'Snapjaw', she is conveyed to fulfill the third by re-uniting the Maerum with the Alatians. After a series of tasks and in meeting with the Alatians' leader, April fulfills their prophecy by flying without wings, and convinces the Alatian to make peace with the Maerum.\n\nIn a coastal sea cave, the Teller's guard and the Maerum Queen bring stones which combine to form the second part of the Balance's disc; whereupon the Maerum convey April, at her own request, to the Blue Dragon, who gives April one of the disc's Jewels and takes her to a ship inhabited by the Dark People, who give April the third piece of the disc, and an astral map locating the Guardian's Realm.\n\nAt the Marcurian Harbor, April is attacked by the Chaos and returns to the Cathedral in Stark. There, Father Raul reveals that he is also a Sentinel Minstrum of Stark, and that Cortez is missing. On returning to her lodgings, April is caught by Gordon Halloway. She is rescued by another character, Lady Alvane, who teaches April to shift at will, and sends April to Abnaxus to receive the disc's final piece. April then returns to the White Dragon, who reveals herself as April's mother and dies, and a new White Dragon emerges from her egg.\n\nReturned to Stark, April gives Flipper the star map to decipher, infiltrates MTI, and is captured by antagonist McAllen. Unable to escape, she surrenders her two jewels and the disc, and is then imprisoned. Upon escaping in pursuit of her object, she is trapped again; but rescued by Cortez. McAllen then reveals that he and Cortez are two Dragons (called 'Draic Kin', in-universe) meant to protect Stark, but at odds after McAllen's decision to re-unite the two worlds despite the risk of Chaos. The two then appear to die in combat. Retrieving the disc and the four jewels, April returns to Flipper, whom she finds dying after the seizure of her deciphered map by Gordon Halloway, and gains a copy from him, which she uses to locate the Guardian's Realm near the [[space station]] 'Morning Star'.\n\nAt the station, April frees Adrian, the derelict Guardian, and escapes with Halloway in pursuit. On her way to the Guardians' Tower, she imprisons the Chaos Vortex in her Talisman and later summons Crow, who helps her complete the necessary trials. Inside the tower, April re-unites Halloway with the Chaos Vortex to restore his candidacy as Guardian and returns to Stark and Arcadia.\n\nIn the Epilogue, the scene returns to Lady Alvane's home, where she has narrated the entire story to two youths, and where she reveals that the two worlds re-united under Gordon Halloway. Upon their departure, an aged and graying Crow enters, asking the tale of the \"[[Women warriors in literature and culture|warrior princess]]\" who won the war of the Balance, and she corrects his impression; a possible reference to the sequel, ''[[Dreamfall: The Longest Journey]]''.\n\n==Development==\nThe title of the game is a reference to the quote by the Swedish diplomat [[Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld]]: \"The longest journey is the journey inward, for he who has chosen his destiny has started upon his quest for the source of his being.\"<ref>{{cite AV media|people=Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist |date=22 February 2013 |title=RedThreadGames: Dreamfall Chapters: The Longest Journey |medium=live stream |url=http://www.twitch.tv/redthreadgames/b/370112870 |accessdate=27 February 2013 |time=10:01:20 |timecaption=Creator commentary starting at |publisher=[[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] |location=Oslo, Norway |display-authors=etal |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130226144439/http://www.twitch.tv/redthreadgames/b/370112870 |archivedate=February 26, 2013 }}</ref> Other inspirations for the game included ''[[Gabriel Knight: Sins of the Fathers]]'', [[Neil Gaiman]]'s ''[[The Sandman (Vertigo)|The Sandman]]'' and ''[[The Books of Magic]]'', ''[[Hellblazer]]'', ''[[Swamp Thing]]'', ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'', and [[Joss Whedon]]'s writing in general.<ref name=\"B\u00f6ke\"/>\n\n''The Longest Journey'' was developed by a small internal team at [[Funcom]] led by [[Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist]]. It was their first original project. Funcom put few restrictions on the developers except the budget (approx. $2\u20133 million) and the deadline. Since the team had to develop the [[game engine]] and most of the required tools from scratch, they struggled to release the game on time. For most of 1999, the team had to work overtime and during weekends to ultimately meet the deadline.<ref name=\"B\u00f6ke\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adventuregamers.com/articles/view/24090 |title=Dreamfall Chapters \u2013 Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist |last=B\u00f6ke |first=Ingmar |date=1 March 2013 |work=[[Adventure Gamers]] |accessdate=1 March 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304061953/http://www.adventuregamers.com/articles/view/24090 |archivedate=March 4, 2013 }}</ref> In the original Norwegian release, April Ryan was voiced by the journalist [[:no:Synn\u00f8ve Svab\u00f8|Synn\u00f8ve Svab\u00f8]].<ref name=dagbladet2>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000308132657/http://www.dagbladet.no:80/kultur/1999/06/30/169622.html | url=http://www.dagbladet.no:80/kultur/1999/06/30/169622.html | title=Synn\u00f8ve blir dataheltinne | date=June 30, 1999 | author=Andersen, Unn Conradi | work=[[Dagbladet]] | language=Norwegian | archivedate=March 8, 2000 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFirst published by IQ Media Nordic in Norway in 1999, it was later localized for and released in France, the United Kingdom, Germany, Italy, Belgium, the Netherlands, Canada, Spain, Denmark, Finland, Sweden, Poland, Czech Republic, Russia, and the United States. The game was originally written and recorded in English, though most of the localizations were released before the English version.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sluganski |first=Randy |title=Interview with Ragnar Tornquist |publisher=Just Adventure + |url=http://www.justadventure.com/Interviews/Ragnar_Tornquist/Ragnar_Tornquist.shtm |accessdate=2011-01-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610135459/http://www.justadventure.com/Interviews/Ragnar_Tornquist/Ragnar_Tornquist.shtm |archivedate=June 10, 2011 }}</ref> In October 2011, it was announced that ''The Longest Journey'' was being ported to [[iOS]], with the article mainly focusing on the [[iPhone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videogamer.com/pc/dreamfall/news/the_longest_journey_coming_to_iphone.html |title=The Longest Journey coming to iPhone - VideoGamer.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710155308/http://www.videogamer.com/pc/dreamfall/news/the_longest_journey_coming_to_iphone.html |archivedate=July 10, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Release and sales==\nBefore its release, ''The Longest Journey'' received positive preview coverage and was heavily promoted in Norway.<ref name=digino1>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050217222220/http://digi.no/php/art.php?id=43949 | url=http://digi.no/php/art.php?id=43949 | title=\"Den lengste reisen\" i m\u00e5l etter halvannen m\u00e5ned | author=Berg, Herman | date=December 29, 1999 | work=[[Digi.no]] | language=Norwegian | archivedate=February 17, 2005 | url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[Dagbladet]]'' described the title as \"the first big Norwegian computer game.\" Its target demographics were outside the industry's norm: Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist reported that Funcom wanted to capture \"a more adult audience in addition to the usual teenage buyers\". The game's high budget meant that 150,000 sales were necessary to [[Break-even|break even]].<ref name=dagbladet1 /> However, Norway's market for games was small.<ref name=digino1 /><ref name=dagbladet1 /> According to Herman Berg of [[Digi.no]], it was rare for a game's Norwegian sales to reach 10,000 units.<ref name=digino1 /> ''The Longest Journey''{{'}}s domestic sales goal was 15,000 units,<ref name=digino1 /><ref name=dagbladet1>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010417122346/http://www.dagbladet.no/kultur/1999/11/19/183637.html | url=http://www.dagbladet.no/kultur/1999/11/19/183637.html | title=Norske April blir data-babe | author=Hanssen, Kurt | date=November 19, 1999 | work=[[Dagbladet]] | language=Norwegian | archivedate=April 17, 2001 | url-status=dead }}</ref> while its global lifetime goal was 300,000 units.<ref name=vg1>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001008063343/http://www.vg.no/pub/vgart.hbs?artid=3762419 | url=http://www.vg.no/pub/vgart.hbs?artid=3762419 | title=Redder verden i norsk dataspill | date=November 19, 1999 | author=Winterkj\u00e6r, St\u00e5le | work=[[Verdens Gang]] | language=Norwegian | archivedate=October 8, 2000 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Funcom shipped 15,000 copies of ''The Longest Journey'' to Norwegian retailers in the game's first month and a half on shelves, and publisher IQ Media noted that [[sell-through]] and store re-orders were high through late December. Sell-in had reached 10,000 units in Sweden by that time. Based on the available data, IQ's Nickolay Nickelsen noted that it \"looks as if half of the players are actually girls.\"<ref name=digino1 />\n\nAccording to T\u00f8rnquist, ''The Longest Journey'' experienced \"solid sales across Europe\" before its release in the United States.<ref name=ragnarint>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050405105813/http://www.justadventure.com/Interviews/Ragnar_Tornquist/Ragnar_Tornquist.shtm | url=http://www.justadventure.com:80/Interviews/Ragnar_Tornquist/Ragnar_Tornquist.shtm | title=Ragnar Tornquist | author=Sluganski, Randy | archivedate=April 5, 2005 | work=[[Just Adventure]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The game sold 15,000 units in Norway by May 2000,<ref name=bonusweb>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000916223844/http://www.bonusweb.cz:80/interview/ragnartornquist.html | url=http://www.bonusweb.cz:80/interview/ragnartornquist.html | title=Ragnar Tornquist o ''The Longest Journey'' | date=May 22, 2000 | author=Tichacek, Petr | work=BonusWeb | archivedate=September 16, 2000 | url-status=dead }}</ref> while overall European sales totaled 100,000 units by September 2000.<ref name=digino2>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050219225758/http://digi.no/digi98.nsf/pub/dd20000928104026pc28450446| url=http://digi.no/digi98.nsf/pub/dd20000928104026pc28450446 | title=Eventyrdame med lang reise til USA | author=Sokke, Christian | date=September 28, 2000 | work=[[Digi.no]] | language=Norwegian | archivedate=February 19, 2005 | url-status=dead }}</ref> It launched in Germany with a shipment of 40,000 units to retailers;<ref name=digino3>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050313185329/http://www.digi.no/digi98.nsf/pub/md20000317010000pcs2703135729| url=http://www.digi.no/digi98.nsf/pub/md20000317010000pcs2703135729 | title=April Ryans lange reise til England | author=Sokke, Christian | date=March 17, 2000 | work=[[Digi.no]] | archivedate=March 13, 2005 | url-status=dead | language=Norwegian }}</ref><ref name=40k>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011211090046/http://www.longestjourney.com:80/news.html | url=http://www.longestjourney.com:80/news.html | title=German release date March 20th | date=February 15, 2000 | archivedate=December 11, 2001 | publisher=[[Funcom]] | url-status=dead }}</ref> Chris Kellner of [[DTP Entertainment]], which handled the game's German localization, reported its lifetime sales between 10,000 and 50,000 copies in that market.<ref name=inv10>{{cite magazine | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060813153740/http://www.justadventure.com:80/TheInventory/TheInventory.shtm | url=http://www.justadventure.com:80/TheInventory/TheInventory.shtm | title=The Lounge; Interview with DTP | date=November 2003 | issue=10 | magazine=The Inventory | publisher=[[Just Adventure]] | archivedate=August 13, 2006 | pages=20\u201323 | url-status=dead }}</ref> In Spain, the game sold 50,000 copies after roughly one year, a commercial hit for the country.<ref name=50k>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040907063053/http://www.meristation.com:80/sc/noticias/noticia.asp?c=GEN&n=3527| url=http://www.meristation.com:80/sc/noticias/noticia.asp?c=GEN&n=3527 | title=''The Longest Journey'' proporciona a FX su cuarto CD-ROM de oro | date=November 14, 2001 | author=Meix, Joan Isern | work=MeriStation | archivedate=September 7, 2004 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Its English release was purposely delayed to prevent imports from [[Cannibalization (marketing)|cannibalizing]] local sales across Europe.<ref name=nettavisen1>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000301145118/http://www.nettavisen.no/it_nyheter/82013.html | url=http://www.nettavisen.no/it_nyheter/82013.html | title=Lettere animert Synn\u00f8ve Svab\u00f8 | author=Heft\u00f8y, Jens Egil | date=November 19, 1999 | work=[[Nettavisen]] | language=Norwegian | archivedate=March 1, 2000 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n''The Longest Journey'' struggled to find a North American publisher.<ref name=granade>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010428224705/http://interactfiction.about.com/games/interactfiction/library/weekly/aa101600a.htm |url=http://interactfiction.about.com/games/interactfiction/library/weekly/aa101600a.htm | title=Journey to America | author=Granade, Stephen | work=[[About.com]] | date=October 16, 2000 | archivedate=April 28, 2001 | url-status=dead }}</ref> According to market research firm [[PC Data]], North American sales of ''The Longest Journey'' reached 12,495 retail units by the end of 2000, of which 10,873 were sold in December.<ref name=randysales>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010414041809/http://justadventure.com/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/01-02/Feb_01.asp | url=http://justadventure.com:80/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/01-02/Feb_01.asp | title=The State of Adventure Gaming | date=February 2001 | author=Sluganski, Randy | archivedate=April 14, 2001 | work=[[Just Adventure]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> By January 2001, global sales of ''The Longest Journey'' totaled almost 200,000 units.<ref name=200k>{{cite press release | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011106042732/http://www.funcom.com:80/corporate/about/pressreleases/100101tljawards.html | url=http://www.funcom.com:80/corporate/about/pressreleases/100101tljawards.html | title=Norsk dataspill til topps i USA | date=January 10, 2001 | location=[[Oslo]] | publisher=[[Funcom]] | archivedate=November 6, 2001 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=digino4>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050217084422/http://www.digi.no/digi98.nsf/pub/dd20010110104314tw36623025 | url=http://www.digi.no/digi98.nsf/pub/dd20010110104314tw36623025 | title=Norsk spill-suksess i USA | author=Werenskiold, Therese | date=January 10, 2001 | work=[[Digi.no]] | language=Norwegian | archivedate=February 17, 2005 | url-status=dead }}</ref> PC Data reported an additional 40,160 retail sales of ''The Longest Journey'' in North America during the first six months of 2001.<ref name=randysales2>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020215014752/http://justadventure.com/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/01-08/August_01.shtm | url=http://justadventure.com:80/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/01-08/August_01.shtm | title=The State of Adventure Gaming | author=Sluganski, Randy | date=August 2001 | archivedate=February 15, 2002 | work=[[Just Adventure]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> By that June, the game's worldwide sales had climbed to 250,000 copies, of which the United States accounted for 90,000.<ref name=gamespotsales>{{cite web |last=Park |first=Andrew |title=''The Longest Journey'' sells 250,000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011126033629/http://gamespot.com/gamespot/stories/news/0,10870,2779455,00.html |url=http://gamespot.com:80/gamespot/stories/news/0,10870,2779455,00.html |archivedate=November 26, 2001 |date=June 22, 2001 |work=[[GameSpot]] |url-status=dead }}</ref> PC Data's estimate for the title's North American sales for January\u2013December 2001 was 71,962 retail units,<ref name=randysales3>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020619111456/http://www.justadventure.com/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/Mar-02/sales2001.shtm | url=http://www.justadventure.com:80/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/Mar-02/sales2001.shtm | title=State of Adventure Gaming - March 2002 - 2001 Sales Table | date=March 2002 | author=Sluganski, Randy | archivedate=June 19, 2002 | work=[[Just Adventure]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> followed by another 12,044 in the first six months of 2002.<ref name=randysales4>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050314010007/http://justadventure.com/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/August2002/SalesJune2002.shtm | url=http://justadventure.com:80/articles/State_of_Adventure_Gaming/August2002/SalesJune2002.shtm | title=State of Adventure Gaming - August 2002 - June 2002 Sales Table | date=August 2002 | author=Sluganski, Randy | archivedate=March 14, 2005 | work=[[Just Adventure]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> By July 2002, global sales of the game had reached 450,000 copies, according to Funcom. A new shipment was released in North America that month, as its earlier printing had sold out.<ref name=450k>{{cite web | title = ''The Longest Journey'' \u2013 General News | publisher = [[Funcom]] | author=Staff | url = http://www.longestjourney.com/news/general/ | date = July 29, 2002 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20021010033406/http://www.longestjourney.com/news/general/ |archivedate = October 10, 2002}}</ref> Ragnar T\u00f8rnquist noted in 2003 that he was \"very satisfied\" with ''The Longest Journey''{{'}}s sales in North America, and explained, \"There was such strong word of mouth, and so many great reviews, that we managed to get ''TLJ'' into most big stores and out to the players regardless of marketing.\"<ref name=ragnarint2>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050308133426/http://www.justadventure.com/Interviews/TLJ2/TLJ2.shtm | url=http://www.justadventure.com:80/Interviews/TLJ2/TLJ2.shtm | title=An Interview with Ragnar Tornquist | date=February 27, 2003 | author=Sluganski, Randy | archivedate=March 8, 2005 | work=[[Just Adventure]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2003, Marek Bronstring of [[Adventure Gamers]] wrote that ''The Longest Journey'' \"sold half a million copies worldwide and it's still selling, making it one of the most successful adventure games in recent years.\"<ref name=tlj2prev>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020085804/http://www.adventuregamers.com/display.php?id=262 | url=http://www.adventuregamers.com/display.php?id=262 | title=''The Longest Journey 2'' Archived Preview | author=Bronstring, Marek | date=May 24, 2003 | work=[[Adventure Gamers]] | archivedate=October 20, 2007 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The following year, [[IGN]] reported that its sales had surpassed 500,000 units. The site's Richard Aihoshi summarized ''The Longest Journey'' as a \"a critical and commercial success\".<ref name=ignint2>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040602200352/http://rpgvault.ign.com/articles/512/512726p1.html | url=http://rpgvault.ign.com:80/articles/512/512726p1.html | title=''Dreamfall - The Longest Journey'' Interview | date=May 10, 2004 | author=Aihoshi, Richard | work=[[IGN]] | archivedate=June 2, 2004 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2019, T\u00f8rnquist recalled that \"at least 50 per cent\" of ''The Longest Journey''{{'}}s players were female, a fact that he believed increased its commercial success.<ref name=retrogamer>{{cite journal | author=Walker-Emig, Paul | title=The Making of ''The Longest Journey'' | date=2019 | issue=191 | work=[[Retro Gamer]] | pages=66\u201369 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| GR = 88.00%<ref name=\"GR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/198973-the-longest-journey/index.html |title=The Longest Journey for PC |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=30 March 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316210557/http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/198973-the-longest-journey/index.html |archivedate=March 16, 2009 }}</ref>\n| MC = 91/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-longest-journey |title=The Longest Journey for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=30 March 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100820025358/http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/the-longest-journey |archivedate=August 20, 2010 }}</ref>\n| CGW = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=cgw>{{cite journal | author=Wells, Audrey | title=Fantastic Voyage | date=January 2001 | issue=198 | journal=[[Computer Gaming World]] | pages=138, 139 }}</ref>\n| AdvGamers = 4.5/5<ref name=\"advgamers_review\">{{cite web|last=Bronstring |first=Marek |date=20 May 2000 |url=http://www.adventuregamers.com/articles/view/17507 |title=The Longest Journey |publisher=[[Adventure Gamers]] |accessdate=30 March 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615113941/http://www.adventuregamers.com/articles/view/17507 |archivedate=June 15, 2012 }}</ref>\n| GSpot = 9.3/10<ref name=\"gamespot review\">{{cite web|last=Dulin |first=Ron |date=26 June 2000 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/pc/adventure/longestjourney/review.html?mode=gsreview |title=The Longest Journey for PC Review |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=29 March 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060619134056/http://www.gamespot.com/pc/adventure/longestjourney/review.html?mode=gsreview |archivedate=June 19, 2006 }}</ref>\n| GSpy = 92/100<ref name=\"gamespy_review\">{{cite web|last=Schembri |first=Tamara |url=http://archive.gamespy.com/legacy/reviews/tlj_a.shtm |title=The Longest Journey |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |accessdate=30 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409005858/http://archive.gamespy.com/legacy/reviews/tlj_a.shtm |archivedate=April 9, 2008 }}</ref>\n| IGN = 9.3/10<ref name=\"ign review\">{{cite web|last=Lopez |first=Vincent |date=20 November 2000 |url=http://pc.ign.com/articles/160/160848p1.html |title=The Longest Journey Review |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=29 March 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509100616/http://pc.ign.com/articles/160/160848p1.html |archivedate=May 9, 2008 }}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 90%<ref name=\"pcgamer us\">{{cite journal |last=Steinberg |first=Scott |date=February 2001 |title=The Longest Journey |journal=[[PC Gamer|PC Gamer US]] |volume=8 |issue=2 |pages=97 |issn=1080-4471 }}</ref>\n| NGen = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=nextgenrev>{{cite journal | author=Bratcher, Eric | title=Finals; ''The Longest Journey'' | date=February 2001 | page=83 | journal=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] | volume=Lifecycle 2, Vol. 3 | number=2 }}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Computer Games Magazine]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=cgm>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040813082453/http://www.cgonline.com/reviews/longestjou-01-r1.html | url=http://www.cgonline.com:80/reviews/longestjou-01-r1.html | title=Review; ''The Longest Journey'' | author=Morgan, Cindy Kyser | date=February 26, 2001 | archivedate=August 13, 2004 | work=[[Computer Games Magazine]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[EP Daily|The Electric Playground]]''\n| rev4Score = 8.5/10<ref name=elecplay>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040126204016/http://elecplay.com/review.html?article=5148 | url=http://www.elecplay.com:80/review.html?article=5148 | title=''The Longest Journey'' | author=Reaume, Paula | date=February 1, 2001 | archivedate=January 26, 2004 | work=[[EP Daily|The Electric Playground]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n\n''The Longest Journey'' was acclaimed by critics. It was praised for its female protagonist [[April Ryan (The Longest Journey)|April Ryan]], who is considered one of the most memorable female characters in the history of [[adventure game]]s,<ref name=\"GPro_TLJ_rev\">{{cite magazine |last=Molloy |first=Sean |date=23 February 2004 |url=http://www.gamepro.com/computer/pc/games/reviews/7526.shtml |title=''The Longest Journey'' review |magazine=[[GamePro]] |accessdate=14 December 2006 |quote=April Ryan is one of the strongest, most well-written, and most likeable heroines ever to point-and-click her way around a PC game. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517050706/http://www.gamepro.com/computer/pc/games/reviews/7526.shtml |archivedate=May 17, 2008 }}</ref> and also for its enigmatic, complex storyline and high production values, but was criticized for some of its more obscure puzzles. It received a score of 88.00% on [[GameRankings]]<ref name=\"GR\" /> and 91/100 on [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MC\" /> [[GameSpot]] called it \"one of the best adventure games in years\" and applauded the \"complex and interesting story\" although found the ending lacking as \"the [[epilogue]] does little to wrap everything up\".<ref name=\"gamespot review\" /> ''[[IGN]]'' said the game \"actually reinvents how stories can be told in the medium\" and noticed the mature content, including \"harsh subject matter, and some big time swearing\". Some of the puzzles were described as \"inane\", but on the whole the game \"hones the genre into its tightest, sharpest form yet\".<ref name=\"ign review\" /> The US edition of ''[[PC Gamer]]'' praised the \"mature and magical\" story, the \"sumptuous\" graphics, and the game's puzzles.<ref name=\"pcgamer us\" /> The only criticism levied by the magazine was that some parts of the game might be \"too edgy\" for younger players.<ref name=\"pcgamer us\" />\n\nEric Bratcher reviewed the PC version of the game for ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'', rating it three stars out of five, and stated that \"This is a potential epic that seems to have taken tranquilizers. It's still worthwhile, but it's also a little slow, a little dull, and sometimes just doesn't make sense.\"<ref name=nextgenrev/>\n\n''The Longest Journey'' was named the best computer adventure game of 2000 by ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'',<ref name=cgwpremier2000>{{cite journal | author=Staff | journal=[[Computer Gaming World]] | title=The 2001 Premier Awards; Games of the Year |date=April 2001 | issue=201 | pages=72\u201380, 82, 83 }}</ref> ''[[EP Daily|The Electric Playground]]'',<ref name=blister2000>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020208192633/http://www.elecplay.com/feature.html?article=5130&page=1 | url=http://www.elecplay.com/feature.html?article=5130&page=1 | title=Blister Awards 2000 | date=February 2001 | author=Staff | work=[[EP Daily|The Electric Playground]] | archivedate=February 8, 2002 | url-status=dead }}</ref> [[GameSpot]],<ref name=gamespot2000>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020202174438/http://gamespot.com/gamespot/features/pc/bestof_2000/index.html |url=http://gamespot.com:80/gamespot/features/pc/bestof_2000/index.html |title=Best and Worst of 2000 |author=GameSpot Staff |work=[[GameSpot]] |archivedate=February 2, 2002 | date=January 5, 2001 | url-status=dead }}</ref> [[IGN]] and ''[[PC Gamer US]]'',<ref name=ignawards2000>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010413122552/http://pc.ign.com/news/30575.html |url=http://pc.ign.com:80/news/30575.html |title=IGNPC's Best of 2000 Awards |author=Staff |work=[[IGN]] |archivedate=April 13, 2001 |date=January 26, 2001 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=pcgseventh>{{cite magazine | title=The Seventh Annual PC Gamer Awards | magazine=PC Gamer | publisher=[[Imagine Media]] | issn=1080-4471 | volume=3 | issue=8 | date=March 2001 }}</ref> and was nominated in the category by [[CNET Gamecenter]] and ''[[Computer Games Magazine]]''.<ref name=cgmnominees>{{cite web |author=Staff |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050209070529/http://www.cdmag.com/articles/031/125/010208-07.html |url=http://www.cdmag.com:80/articles/031/125/010208-07.html |title=''Computer Games Magazine'' announces nominees for annual best in computer gaming awards |date=February 8, 2001 |work=[[Computer Games Magazine]] |archivedate=February 9, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=gamecenter2000>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010208100435/http://www.gamecenter.com/Features/Exclusives/Awards2k/ | url=http://www.gamecenter.com:80/Features/Exclusives/Awards2k/ | title=Gamecenter's computer game awards for 2000 | author=The Gamecenter Editors | work=[[CNET Gamecenter]] | date=January 25, 2001 | archivedate=February 8, 2001 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> It also won IGN's \"Best Game No One Played\" and GameSpot's \"Best Story\" awards.<ref name=ignawards2000 /><ref name=gamespot2000 /> ''Computer Gaming World''{{'}}s editors praised the game for offering \"a mature, literate, and compelling story featuring a strong female heroine who, for once, is not exploited for her looks.\"<ref name=cgwpremier2000 />\n\nIn 2011, [[Adventure Gamers]] named ''The Longest Journey'' the second-best adventure game ever released.<ref name=top100>{{cite web | author=AG Staff | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604021011/http://www.adventuregamers.com/articles/view/18643 | url=http://www.adventuregamers.com/articles/view/18643 | title=Top 100 All-Time Adventure Games | date=December 30, 2011 | archivedate=June 4, 2012 | work=[[Adventure Gamers]] | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Sequels==\nA sequel to ''The Longest Journey'' began production in early 2003.<ref name=dagbladet3>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050421224201/http://www.dagbladet.no:80/kultur/2003/03/01/362829.html| url=http://www.dagbladet.no:80/kultur/2003/03/01/362829.html | title=Den ''lengste'' lengste reisen | author=Bryne, Snorre | date=March 1, 2003 | work=[[Dagbladet]] | archivedate=April 21, 2005 | language=Norwegian | url-status=dead }}</ref> The game, ''[[Dreamfall: The Longest Journey]]'', was released in April 2006. The next installment of the series, ''[[Dreamfall Chapters]]'', was crowd-funded on [[Kickstarter]] and was released [[episodic video game|episodically]]. Its first episode was released in October 2014.<ref name=\"DFC_Kickstarter\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/redthread/dreamfall-chapters-the-longest-journey |title=Dreamfall Chapters: The Longest Journey |last=Red Thread Games |date=8 February 2013 |work=[[Kickstarter]] |accessdate=8 February 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130211002220/http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/redthread/dreamfall-chapters-the-longest-journey |archivedate=February 11, 2013 }}</ref> The last episode shipped in June 2016.\n\nThe developers view ''Dreamfall: The Longest Journey'' as more of a [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] than a direct [[sequel]] to the first game, as it revolves around a new protagonist, with a new storyline.<ref name=\"B\u00f6ke\" /> The direct sequel to ''The Longest Journey'', entitled ''The Longest Journey Home'', was revealed in 2013 and is to be produced after ''Dreamfall Chapters''.<ref name=\"TLJHome\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/features/taking-the-longest-journey-home-6404653/ |title=Taking The Longest Journey Home |last=VanOrd |first=Kevin |date=1 March 2013 |work=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=4 March 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304090413/http://www.gamespot.com/features/taking-the-longest-journey-home-6404653/ |archivedate=March 4, 2013 }}</ref> By 2016 the release of TLJHome is still under a question. Ragnar Tornquist stated that even though he wants to produce the game, there are many reasons why it may never happen.<ref name=\"Hillier2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2016/06/10/dreamfall-chapters-teaser-heralds-the-end-of-the-longest-journey/ |title=Dreamfall Chapters teaser heralds the end of The Longest Journey |last=Hillier |first=Brenna |date=10 June 2016 |work=[[VG247]] |accessdate=13 June 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611142231/http://www.vg247.com/2016/06/10/dreamfall-chapters-teaser-heralds-the-end-of-the-longest-journey/ |archivedate=June 11, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"O'Connor\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/06/10/when-does-dreamfall-chapters-book-five-come-out/ |title=Dreamfall Chapters Ending Longest Journey Next Week |last=O'Connor |first=Alice |date=10 June 2016 |work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] |accessdate=17 June 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611135824/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/06/10/when-does-dreamfall-chapters-book-five-come-out/ |archivedate=June 11, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Runaway: A Road Adventure]]''\n*''[[Syberia]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.longestjourney.com}}\n* {{moby game|id=/longest-journey}}\n\n{{The Longest Journey}}\n{{Funcom}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Longest Journey, The}}\n[[Category:1999 video games]]\n[[Category:Funcom games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Point-and-click adventure games]]\n[[Category:The Longest Journey games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Norway]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female protagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring parallel universes]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:ResidualVM supported games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:anchor.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Longest_Journey"}
{"title_page": "Shorea siamensis", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| status = LR/lc\n| status_system = IUCN2.3\n| genus = Shorea\n| species = siamensis\n| authority = [[Friedrich Anton Wilhelm Miquel|Miq.]]\n}}\n\n'''''Shorea siamensis''''' (called, along with some other species in the genus ''[[Shorea]]'', '''dark red meranti''', '''light red meranti''', or '''red lauan''') is a species of [[plant]] in the family [[Dipterocarpaceae]]. The tree is growing in most of [[Southeast Asia]] and is found in [[Myanmar]], [[Malaysia]], [[Thailand]], [[Cambodia]], [[Vietnam]] and [[Indonesia]].\n\n== Uses ==\nIn Cambodia, this tree is rare and most often seen near Buddhist pagodas and shrines. According to legend one of [[Buddha]]'s incarnations was born under an ''s. siamensis'' tree and therefore it has a strong symbolic connection to Cambodia's Buddhist culture. The leaves of the tree are used in [[traditional Cambodian medicine]] as a tea for easing child birth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tentree.com/blog/trees-plant-cambodia/ |title=types of trees we plant in Cambodia |publisher=tentree |date=4 May 2015 |accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Names ==\nThe tree is known by various local names:\n* [[Khmer language|Khmer]]: \u1788\u17be\u1798\u17d2\u179a\u17b6\u17c6\u1784\u1797\u17d2\u17c2\u17b6\u17c6 (Raing Phnom)<ref>{{cite paper|url=http://ffish.asia/pdfs/PicturedGuide_KgChhnang.pdf |title=A pictured guide of forest trees in Cambodia I |page=37 |accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Thai language|Thai]]: {{lang|th|\u0e23\u0e31\u0e07}} ({{RTGS|''rang''}}, {{IPA-th|r\u0101\u014b|pron}})\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{Cite iucn | author = Ashton, P. | title = ''Shorea siamensis'' | volume = 1998 | page = e.T32307A9694077 | date = 1998 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.1998.RLTS.T32307A9694077.en }}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1329842}}\n\n[[Category:Shorea|siamensis]]\n[[Category:Trees of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Trees of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Trees of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Trees of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Trees of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Least concern plants]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Dipterocarpaceae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| status = LR/lc\n| status_system = IUCN2.3\n| genus = Shorea\n| species = siamensis\n| authority = [[Friedrich Anton Wilhelm Miquel|Miq.]]\n}}\n\n'''''Shorea siamensis''''' (called, along with some other species in the genus ''[[Shorea]]'', '''dark red meranti''', '''light red meranti''', or '''red lauan''') is a species of [[plant]] in the [[Dipterocarpaceae]] family. The tree is growing in most of [[Southeast Asia]] and is found in [[Myanmar]], [[Malaysia]], [[Thailand]], [[Cambodia]], [[Vietnam]] and [[Indonesia]].\n\n== Uses ==\nIn Cambodia, this tree is rare and most often seen near Buddhist pagodas and shrines. According to legend one of [[Buddha]]'s incarnations was born under an ''s. siamensis'' tree and therefore it has a strong symbolic connection to Cambodia's Buddhist culture. The leaves of the tree are used in [[traditional Cambodian medicine]] as a tea for easing child birth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tentree.com/blog/trees-plant-cambodia/ |title=types of trees we plant in Cambodia |publisher=tentree |date=4 May 2015 |accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Names ==\nThe tree is known by various local names:\n* [[Khmer language|Khmer]]: \u1788\u17be\u1798\u17d2\u179a\u17b6\u17c6\u1784\u1797\u17d2\u17c2\u17b6\u17c6 (Raing Phnom)<ref>{{cite paper|url=http://ffish.asia/pdfs/PicturedGuide_KgChhnang.pdf |title=A pictured guide of forest trees in Cambodia I |page=37 |accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Thai language|Thai]]: {{lang|th|\u0e23\u0e31\u0e07}} ({{RTGS|''rang''}}, {{IPA-th|r\u0101\u014b|pron}})\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{Cite iucn | author = Ashton, P. | title = ''Shorea siamensis'' | volume = 1998 | page = e.T32307A9694077 | date = 1998 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.1998.RLTS.T32307A9694077.en }}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1329842}}\n\n[[Category:Shorea|siamensis]]\n[[Category:Trees of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Trees of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Trees of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Trees of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Trees of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Least concern plants]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Dipterocarpaceae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shorea_siamensis"}
{"title_page": "Vicecomodoro \u00c1ngel de la Paz Aragon\u00e9s Airport", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Vicecomodoro \u00c1ngel de la Paz Aragon\u00e9s Airport\n| nativename   = {{small|{{lang|es|Aeropuerto de Santiago del Estero}}}}\n| IATA         = SDE\n| ICAO         = SANE\n| type         = Public\n| owner        = \n| operator     = [[Aeropuertos Argentina 2000]]\n| city-served  = [[Santiago del Estero]], [[Argentina]]\n| location     = \n| metric-elev  = \n| elevation-f  = 659\n| elevation-m  = \n| coordinates  = {{coord|27|46|00|S|64|18|35|W|region:FR-U|display=inline,title}}\n| website      = \n| pushpin_map            = Argentina\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Airport in Argentina\n| pushpin_label          = '''SDE'''\n| pushpin_label_position = top\n| metric-rwy   = y\n| r1-number    = 03/21\n| r1-length-m  = 2635\n| r1-length-f  = \n| r1-surface   = Asphalt\n| stat-year    = 2016\n| stat1-header = Total passengers\n| stat1-data   = 94,980\n| footnotes    = Sources: ORSNA,<ref name=ORSNA>{{in lang|es}} ''[https://archive.is/20121126222229/http://www.orsna.gov.ar/aeropuertos/infoaeropuertos.asp?id_aeropuerto=46 Aeropuerto de Santiago del Estero \"Vcom. Angel de la Paz Aragones\" ]'' at ''Organismo Regulador del Sistema Nacional de Aeropuertos (ORSNA)''</ref> WAD<ref name=WAD>{{WAD|SANE|Vicecomodoro \u00c1ngel de la Paz Aragon\u00e9s Airport}}</ref> GCM<ref name=GCM>{{GCM|SDE|Vicecomodoro \u00c1ngel de la Paz Aragon\u00e9s Airport}}</ref> Google Maps<ref>{{cite web |title=Santiago del Estero Airport |url=https://www.google.com/maps/@-27.7658698,-64.3100022,5111m/data=!3m1!1e3 |website=Google Maps |publisher=Google |accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Vicecomodoro \u00c1ngel de la Paz Aragon\u00e9s Airport''' ({{lang-es|link=no|Aeropuerto de Santiago del Estero \u2013 \u00c1ngel de la Paz Aragon\u00e9s}}) {{airport codes|SDE|SANE}} is located {{convert|6|km|0}} northwest of downtown [[Santiago del Estero]], the capital of [[Santiago del Estero Province]] in [[Argentina]]. The airport covers an area of 526 hectares (1299 acres) and is operated by [[Aeropuertos Argentina 2000]].<ref name=ORSNA />\n\nAlso known as '''Santiago del Estero Airport''' or '''Mal Paso Airport''', it was built in 1959 and the runway was re-paved in 2001. It has a {{convert|1000|m2}} terminal and 45 parking spaces. In 2007, it handled 49,517 passengers. The airport does not handle international flights. It is served by [[Flybondi]] [[737-800]] and [[Austral L\u00edneas A\u00e9reas]] [[Embraer 190]].\n\nRunway length includes a {{convert|200|m}} [[Runway#blastpad|blast pad]] on Runway 03. Runway 03 has an additional {{convert|200|m}} paved overrun. The Santiago Del Estero [[VHF omnidirectional range|VOR]] (Ident: '''SDE''') and [[non-directional beacon]] (Ident: '''D''') are located on the field.<ref>{{cite web |title=Santiago Del Estero NDB |url=http://ourairports.com/navaids/D/Santiago_Del_Estero_NDB_AR/ |website=Our Airports |accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Santiago Del Estero VOR |url=http://ourairports.com/navaids/SDE/Santiago_Del_Estero_VOR_AR/ |website=Our Airports |accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n{{airport-dest-list\n|[[Aerol\u00edneas Argentinas]] <br>operated by [[Austral L\u00edneas A\u00e9reas]] | [[Aeroparque Jorge Newbery|Buenos Aires\u2013Aeroparque]]\n|[[Flybondi]] | [[El Palomar Airport|Buenos Aires\u2013El Palomar]]<ref>[https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/276661/flybondi-outlines-operational-launch-in-1h18/ Flybondi begin service to Santiago del Estero]</ref>\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*{{portal-inline|Argentina}}\n*{{portal-inline|Aviation}}\n*[[Transport in Argentina]]\n*[[List of airports in Argentina]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.openstreetmap.org/#map=13/-27.7662/-64.3107 OpenStreetMap - Santiago del Estero Airport]\n*[http://ourairports.com/airport